            "title": "At the heart of the state : the moral world of institutions",
            "abstract": [
                "The state is often regarded as an abstract and neutral bureaucratic entity. Against this common sense idea, At the Heart of the State argues that it is also a concrete and situated reality, embodied in the work of its agents and inscribed in the issues of its time. The result of a five-year investigation conducted by ten scholars, this book describes and analyses the police, the court system, the prison apparatus, the social services, and mental health facilities in France. Combining genealogy and ethnography, its authors show that these state institutions do not simply implement laws, rules and procedures: they mobilise values and affects, judgements and emotions. In other words, they reflect the morality of the state. Of immense interest to both social scientists and political theorists, this work will make an important contribution to the ever expanding literature on the contemporary state.--",
                "Can states be moral? Preface to the English edition / Didier Fassin -- Introduction : Governing precarity / Didier Fassin -- The right to punish : assessing sentences in immediate appearance trials / Chowra Makaremi -- Justice for immigrants : the work of magistrates in deportation proceedings / Nicolas Fischer -- In search of truth : how asylum applications are adjudicated / Carolina Kobelinsky -- Maintaining order : the moral justifications for police practices / Didier Fassin -- Sanctioning behind bars : the humanization of retribution in prison / Fabrice Fernandez -- Assisting or controlling? When social workers become probation officers / Yasmine Bouagga -- Discipline and educate : contradictions within the juvenile justice system / S\u00e9bastien Roux -- Listening to suffering : the treatment of mental fragility at a home for adolescents / Isabelle Coutant and Jean-S\u00e9bastien Eideliman -- Profiling job seekers : the counseling of youths at an employment center / Sarah Mazouz"
            ],
